CS 111, Lab 1a, Srikanth Ashtalakshmi V Rajendran (UID: 804478782)

The program can perform its intended task given correct inputs. In case of errors in the input,
the program may or may not provide a correct output depending on the errors' effect on other
options.

The program generally handles errors by displaying an appropriate error message, and moving on to
the next option in the input. A list of errors that the program handles is shown below.

- No argument(s) provided when an option needs atleast one
- Improper syntax for options and their arguments
- Invalid options
- Attempting to open a file that doesn't exist
- Use of invalid file descriptors in --command option
- Invalid command arguments to the --command option
- Failure when forking a process
- Failure in memory reallocation
